"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:1.2.6\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">1.2.6</span> Bit and bridle</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מֶתֶג</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(metheg)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs19:28\">2KI 19:28</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps32:9\">PSA 32:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov26:3\">PRO 26:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa37:29\">ISA 37:29</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">רֶסֶן</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(resen)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job41:5\">JOB 41:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps32:9\">PSA 32:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa30:28\">ISA 30:28</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">χαλινός</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(chalinos)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jas3:3\">JAS 3:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:20\">REV 14:20</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">χρυσοχάλινος</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(chrusochalinos)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Macc10:29\">2MA 10:29</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Esd3:6\">1ES 3:6</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">κόσμος</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(kosmos)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Macc5:3\">2MA 5:3</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">σαγή</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(sagē)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Macc3:25\">2MA 3:25</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/UBS-0009_bronze_horse_bit.jpg\" alt=\"Ancient bronze horse bit\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Ancient bronze horse bit (© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart by United Bible Societies)</figcaption></figure>The bit was a short bar, usually made of metal, placed in the mouth of a horse. Its ends, which projected from the mouth of the animal, were attached to ropes or leather straps that fitted over the head as the bridle.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0969_harness_bridle_en.jpg\" alt=\"Harness with bridle and bit fitted on the horse&#x27;s head\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Harness with bridle and bit fitted on the horse&#x27;s head (© Gary Todd - Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>By pulling on the bridle straps to the right or left, the rider or driver of the wagon could control the actions of the horse.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0932_horse.jpg\" alt=\"Horse and rider showing use of reins\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Horse and rider showing use of reins (© Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>The Hebrew words <em>metheg</em> and <em>resen</em> respectively refer to the “bit” and “bridle” (although <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr> has once rendered <em>metheg</em> as “bridle” in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov26:3\">PRO 26:3</a>). The Greek words <em>chalinos</em> and <em>chrusochalinos</em> refer to both the bit and bridle. Where a bit or bridle as a piece of harness is unknown, translators can use a descriptive phrase, such as “something to guide a horse with” or “something to put in the mouth of a horse to guide it.”</p>\n<p>The Hebrew word <em>mtsilah</em> in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech14:20\">ZEC 14:20</a> probably refers to some sort of noise-making decoration on the harness of a horse. The word occurs only here in the Bible.</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:20\">REV 14:20</a> the reference to “a horse’s bridle” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>) is merely an indication of measurement. It refers to the height of the bridle from the ground, so we may render this measurement as “about a meter and a half” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"French Common Language Version (Bible en français courant)\">FRCL</abbr>) or “about five feet” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>).</p>\n<p>The Greek word used in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Macc10:29\">2MA 10:29</a> and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Esd3:6\">1ES 3:6</a> indicates that the metal parts of the bridle were made of gold.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
